snippet.textDisplay: Putting the head gasket chemical into the reservoir is not a good plan, IMO.  A large quantity of it will be pushed out and never find it's way to the problem area.  Best to remove a large hose and put it directly into the system so it will flow to where it is needed.  If the expansion reservoir is under pressure, very little of what you want to happen will occur.  Note that the instructions say to "Top Off the Radiator".  Adding to the reservoir is not at all the same.

snippet.textDisplay: WOAHHH, that first fix you had to do with the oil I had that same exact problem on my 2003 lincoln town car. Dealership wanted 1000 to do it, private mechanic wanted 500. I went to Homedepot and bought a few different pipe fittings. I cant remember the exact size that worked but I smashed out the weak parts of the plastic, installed new screw clamps around the pipe (scotty would kill me for doing it) and clamped it around the solid metal pipe which I shoved in as far as I could and threaded into the plastic by twisting it as best as possible. Then I covered the whole pipe with High pressure High temperature putty (i can only find it at autozone) the cheap stuff you get at walmart holds up but will wear out after 2 years or so. Been running fine since I did the fix. I did have to change the plugs and coils because coolant got into the plugs but It was time to replace them anyways. Just thought I'd share in case anyone has a pipe burst on them that goes into a plastic fitting which will cost an insane amount to fix, The cost was probably around 20 dollars with all the parts I bought for the pipe fix. then about 100 for plugs and coils.
